🚨 UNICEF Data Story: The Crisis of Severe Wasting¶

Wasting is the most life-threatening form of malnutrition.

👉 1 in every 13 children suffers from wasting — a condition where children become dangerously thin for their height, leaving them highly vulnerable to disease and death.

📝 This report leverages data from UNICEF, World Bank, and Kaggle to uncover alarming global patterns in child malnutrition.

  • Revealing how poverty, conflict, & geography shape a child’s chance of survival.

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# aggregate
df = (
    pd.read_csv('/content/indicator_2_cleaned.csv')
      .query("Sex=='Total' & Age_Group=='Under 5 years old' & year_final.between(2017,2022)")
      .groupby('Country', as_index=False)['Value']
      .mean()
)

# choropleth world chart
fig = px.choropleth(
    df,
    locations='Country',
    locationmode='country names',
    color='Value',
    color_continuous_scale='Viridis',
    projection='natural earth'
)

# layout
fig.update_layout(
    title={
        'text': "<b>Average Severe Wasting % (2017–22)</b><br>Among Children Under 5",
        'x': 0.5
    },
    margin=dict(l=0, r=0, t=80, b=0)
)

# title and layout
fig.update_coloraxes(colorbar_title_text="<i>Avg Severe Wasting (%)</i>")
fig.update_geos(showframe=False, showcoastlines=False)

fig.show()

🌍 Global Map Highlights¶

Severe Wasting Hotspots
Sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia bear the heaviest burden as seen in the map (unshaded areas indicate lack of data), which will further be explored in the next visualisation.

Why It Matters?

  • The worst-off countries suffer 5 times higher rates than the lowest-risk regions.
  • Reveals entrenched cycles of poverty, conflict and food insecurity.

The global chart echoes Tableau findings: urgent, targeted nutrition interventions are needed where children’s lives are most at risk.

import pandas as pd
from plotnine import (
    ggplot, aes, geom_col, geom_text, coord_flip,
    theme_minimal, labs, scale_y_continuous,
    theme, element_text
)

# Load
df = pd.read_csv('/content/indicator_2_cleaned.csv')
df = df[
    (df.Sex == 'Total') &
    (df.Age_Group == 'Under 5 years old') &
    df.year_final.between(2017, 2022)
]

# Top 5 mean value and  labels
top5 = (
    df.groupby('Country', as_index=False)['Value']
      .mean()
      .nlargest(5, 'Value')
)
top5['label'] = top5['Value'].round(1).astype(int).astype(str) + '%'

# Labels on each bar end
(
    ggplot(top5, aes(x='reorder(Country, Value)', y='Value'))
    + geom_col(fill='crimson')
    + geom_text(
        aes(label='label'),
        va='center',
        ha='left',
        nudge_y=0.2,
        size=6
      )
    + coord_flip()
    + scale_y_continuous(
        labels=lambda vals: [f"{int(v)}%" for v in vals],
        expand=(0, 0.15)
      )
    + theme_minimal()
    + labs(
        title='Top 5 Countries by Avg Severe Wasting (2017–22)',
        subtitle='Among Children Under-5',
        x='Country',
        y='Avg Severe Wasting (%)'
    )
    + theme(
        plot_title=element_text(weight='bold', size=14),
        plot_subtitle=element_text(face='italic', size=10),
        axis_text=element_text(size=8)
    )
)

📊 Top 5 Countries by Average Severe Wasting (2017–22)¶

Among Children under-5 👶

This bar chart shows the five countries with the highest mean rates of severe wasting among under-5s between 2017 and 2022:

  • India leads at 6%, more than twice the global average.
  • Guinea, Malaysia, and Indonesia cluster around 3–3.5%, indicating significant pockets of acute malnutrition outside the world’s poorest nations.
    -Oman rounds out the top five at 3%, underscoring that even middle-income countries face child nutrition challenges.

⚠️ Insight:
These numbers reveal scale and geographic diversity of severe wasting: the most critical hotspots lie in South Asia, meaning that urgent interventions are vital to reduce life-threatening under-nutrition among the youngest children. 👶❤️

import pandas as pd
from plotnine import (
    ggplot, aes, geom_point, geom_smooth,
    scale_color_brewer, theme_minimal,
    labs, theme, element_text, element_rect
)

# Load wasting data & year_min/year_max
ind = pd.read_csv('/content/indicator_2_cleaned.csv')
years = ind['year_final'].dropna().astype(int)
year_min, year_max = years.min(), years.max()

# severe-wasting percentages
wdf = (
    ind[(ind.Sex=='Total') & (ind.Age_Group=='Under 5 years old')]
      [['Country','year_final','Value']]
      .rename(columns={'Value':'waste_pct'})
)

# GDP per capita
wb = pd.read_csv('/content/world_bank_cleaned.csv')
gdf = (
    wb[wb.year.between(year_min, year_max)]
      [['country','year','gpd_per_capita']]
      .rename(columns={'country':'Country','year':'year_final'})
)

# Load continent legend
cont = (
    pd.read_csv('/content/continent_pop.csv')
      .rename(columns={'Country/Territory':'Country'})
      [['Country','Continent']]
)

# Merge
df_full = (
    wdf
      .merge(gdf, on=['Country','year_final'])
      .merge(cont, on='Country')
      .dropna()
)

# Plot scatter + regression line
(
    ggplot(df_full, aes(x='gpd_per_capita', y='waste_pct', color='Continent'))
    + geom_point(size=3, alpha=0.6)
    + geom_smooth(method='lm', se=False, color='red', size=1)
    + scale_color_brewer(type='qual', palette='Set2')
    + theme_minimal()
    + labs(
        title=f'GDP per Capita vs Severe Wasting ({year_min}–{year_max})',
        subtitle='Among Children Under-5',
        x='GDP per Capita (USD)',
        y='Severe Wasting (%)',
        color='Continent'
    )
    + theme(
        plot_title=element_text(weight='bold', size=14),
        plot_subtitle=element_text(face='italic', size=10),
        legend_background=element_rect(fill='white', colour='black'),
        legend_key_size=12
    )
)

🌍 GDP per Capita vs Severe Wasting (1983–2022)¶

Among Children Under-5

This scatterplot shows every country-year data point (1983–2022), colored by continent, with a red regression line illustrating the overall relationship between economic wealth and child malnutrition:

  • 📉 Downward trend: Higher GDP per capita generally corresponds to lower severe wasting rates.
  • 🌍 Low-income hotspots: Many African and Asian countries cluster at GDP < $5 000 with wasting rates above 2–3 %.
  • 💰 Wealth buffer: High-income nations (e.g., USA, Japan, Kuwait) hover near 0–1 % wasting, highlighting how resources protect child nutrition.
  • ⚠️ Key outlier: South Sudan exhibits very high wasting despite low GDP, signaling acute humanitarian crises.

💡 Insight:
Economic development is a powerful lever for reducing life-threatening malnutrition. Targeting low-GDP, high-wasting regions could save hundreds of thousands of young lives each year.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from plotnine import (
    ggplot, aes, geom_line, geom_point,
    scale_color_gradient, theme_minimal,
    labs, theme, element_text
)

# historical series
ind = pd.read_csv('/content/indicator_2_cleaned.csv')
ts = (
    ind.query("Sex=='Total' & Age_Group=='Under 5 years old'")
      .groupby('year_final', as_index=False)['Value']
      .mean()
      .rename(columns={'Value':'avg_waste'})
)
# fit trend
coef = np.polyfit(ts.year_final, ts.avg_waste, 1)
# 20-year forecast
year_max = ts.year_final.max()
pred = pd.DataFrame({
    'year_final': np.arange(year_max+1, year_max+21),
    'avg_waste': coef[0]*np.arange(year_max+1, year_max+21) + coef[1]
})

# plot with continuous gradient on both segments
(
    ggplot(ts, aes(x='year_final', y='avg_waste', color='year_final'))
    + geom_line(size=1.2)
    + geom_point(size=2)
    + geom_line(
        aes(x='year_final', y='avg_waste', color='year_final'),
        data=pred, linetype='dashed', size=1
      )
    + scale_color_gradient(low='lightblue', high='darkblue', name='Year')
    + theme_minimal()
    + labs(
        title='Global Avg Wasting Over Time + 20-Year Forecast',
        subtitle='Among Children Under-5',
        x='Year',
        y='Avg Severe Wasting (%)'
    )
    + theme(
        plot_title=element_text(weight='bold', size=14),
        plot_subtitle=element_text(face='italic', size=10)
    )
)

Global Avg Severe Wasting Over Time + 20-Year Forecast¶

Among Children Under-5

This time series tracks the yearly global average of severe wasting (1983–2022) and projects the next 20 years:

  • 📉 Historical trend: A steady decline from ~3.4 % in the mid-1990s to ~1.2 % by 2022.
  • 🔮 Forecast: Slight spike up but then gradual decrease through 2042.
  • 🌟 Insight: Progress is real but slow—accelerated interventions are needed to drive faster reductions and meet child‐nutrition targets.
